[[File:Ulysses, 1922.djvu|thumb|600px|center|page=274]]
<br>
==Annotations==
'''''Qui sdegno'''''{{spaces|5}}(''Italian'') ''Here indignation''.<ref>Gifford (1988) 306.<br>Thornton (1968) .</ref> These are the opening words of the Italian version of Sarastro's aria ''In diesen heil'gen Hallen'' (''In these sacred halls'') from Act II of [[w:Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart's]] Singspiel ''[[w:Die Zauberflöte|Die Zauberflöte]]'' (''The Magic Flute'').<ref>[http://www.aria-database.com/search.php?individualAria=202 ''In diesen heil'gen Hallen''.]<br>[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:vaZleM4HCpoJ:vocalsheetmusic.net/classical/m/mozart/qui-sdegno-non-saccende.pdf+&hl=en&gl=ie&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESiEH8BaK92cImsalpPsYNeVmIjrTnd7tQUvQ7t5PU5RurGClnLbchWiVLss9zjOavUx7rIkq9oIM596gxRVA3QziF5ygA3bEqKDUPL2q7HdSWb-tYK_XPHheFlrbtDExsf_kIAa&sig=AHIEtbQFzvXffqVdhdI5ugaKh7vsFqxqQg ''Qui sdegno''.]</ref> Here, ''[[wikt:sdegno|sdegno]]'' (''anger'', ''indignation'') corresponds to the German ''[[wikt:Rache|Rache]]'', which can mean ''fury'' or ''rage'', but in this context means ''vengeance''.

